<br>
If a Jewish boy is a man after his Bar Mitz 'vah (sp?) and a Mormon child is considered at age 8 to be intellectually, emotionally and socially mature enough to make decisions about his/her eternal soul then do these groups support or object to trying 8 year olds (or 12 year olds) as adults? Why? If you can understand and articulate about concepts such as justice, peace, god, spirits etc. and make the most important decision of your life about it and you demonstrate to elders that you know what is right and wrong why treat you differently under the law?<br>
<br>
P.S. I disagree 8 year old children fully understand these things and can make decisions like an adult would, so I don't want kids tried as adults--but I'm an atheist.<br>
<br>
