<br>
Well baptising isn't a legal issue, but if you mean change the age of consent then 18 doesn't sound bad to me. I could even sort of see 15 or 16 since I'm also more inclined to think a 16 year old is mature enough to be tried as an adult (I guess I don't equate physically and mentally mature teens with children). I don't remember the age for JWs but even if 18 were a little older than necessary for some that might be ready at 16 or 17, what's the terrible harm in waiting? I'm curious if you apply this to ANY other area of life...after all isn't this decision more important than picking a car or job?<br>
<br>
You must be 16 to work and drive.<br>
You must be 18 to legally engage in commerce like contracts without a co-signer.<br>
You must be 21 to drink (in most places, I know it's 19 in others)<br>
You must be-what is it 17? to see a rated R movie.<br>
You must be 18 to marry in most states or rent an apartment.<br>
You are 17 or 18 when attending college.<br>
You must be 18 to go to war.<br>
<br>
Would you let an 8 year old make ANY of these decisions? Would you consider him mentally, physically or socially mature, informed or in any way prepared?<br>
<br>
Oh---I forgot another interesting fact...LDS missionaries (according to their own site) go on their missions at age 19 for men and 21 for women (I know you can go later, but this is the minimun age right??). Seems so much more logical to me to have a mission follow a major commitment to a belief system--like baptism so 18 sounds pretty darn appropriate to me.<br>
<br>
