<br>
As an aside, I am sickened every time the media reports another story of a minor being tried as an adult.  We have a juvenile justice system for a reason.  IMO, it is not simply that children have an inferior capacity to understand the ramifications of their actions or their own personal responsibility to act in accordance with the laws (though these are certainly valid arguments) but that, when a minor commits a crimes, there are other entities who must necessarily share in the blame -- who failed in providing this child an appropriate gauge for right and wrong.<br>
<br>
My father does criminal defense work, much of which is pro-bono.  He has clients whose parents put beer in their baby bottles to make them sleepy and easier to manage, who've bounced through foster home after foster home after their parents are jailed for drug use, who've grown up with no stable home life and an anemic education in inner-city schools.  Then, when they wind up in trouble with the law, we say, &quot;They should have known better.  Try that 15 year old as an adult.&quot;<br>
 <br>
