Just wanted to jump in here. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   JWs don't have a specific age that we have to wait for.  It is more like we wait until we know that there is understanding.  Before anyone is baptized we go over some Bible based questions with the Elders in our congregation.  This way we have to actually &quot;prove&quot; our understanding of our beliefs before we make type of committment.  <br>
<br>
My husband was raised as a Witness and he was baptized at the age of 15.  I have seen some that are younger, some where around 12 at the yougest, but it is the personal choice of the parent and Elders of that congregation.  I am personally going to have my kids wait until they are older.  <br>
<br>
My oldest daughter is a people pleaser and at this point I know that she would do it for me, but I want her to do it for herself.  My ex-husband is not a Witness and, as you can imagine, has some problems with his kids being raised as such. (He should have thought about that before he decided to have an affair for over a year with my so-called friend.)  So my kids have some real issues to deal with and he will have an influence in thier lives.  I want thier decision to be well educated and know all of the factors in mind before that decision is made.<br>
<br>
Anyway, that is my little tangent, sorry to go off like that. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
