tori amos</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=luvthatdyl>LuvThatDyl</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 12<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/9/03 3:14 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=52.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   accountability</span><hr size=1> I think that just because a child reaches a &quot;religious maturity&quot;, that doesn't mean they are mature enough to go out and conquer the world.  I was never bat mitzvahed since we weren't a religious family.  I went to one year of Hebrew school, and I told my mom I didn't want to do it anymore.  She didn't force me.  If I would have continued Hebrew school, then I would have gone from age 8 to 12, and then been bat mitzvahed after that.  The bat mitzvah would have been my sign to the world that I know how to read and comprehend the Torah, not that I was ready to go out and vote or buy beer.  I do feel that at age 12 and 13 there are certain aspects of life a child should know better about, and one could argue that in that sense they have reached part of their adulthood.  I knew that killing was wrong.  I knew that stealing was wrong.  There are a lot of issues I knew better about, and it didn't take any religious scripture to tell me that.  If I would have decided to go out and commit murder at 13, then I would have done it knowing full well the magnitude of my actions, along with the consequences.  I believe that juvenile laws should be in place to protect kids from the stupid little mistakes kids make.  When I was 15, I was on a fieldtrip at Disneyland, and the group of kids I was with started shoplifting.  I knew better than to steal, and I should have walked away and hung out with another group, but I instead got caught up in it, and we had a good time until we got busted lifting just one more thing on the way back to the bus.  We didn't get arrested, but if we would have gotten arrested, then I would have been glad that those records would have been sealed by my 18th birthday.  I don't look at murder the same way I do shoplifting because shoplifting is just an inconsiderate act instead of a cruel one with the intention to hurt someone else.  I got suspended from school, grounded for a month and totally mortified on my high school campus because everyone knew about it.  I learned from this mistake pretty quick, and there was no need to have it disrupt my entire life.  I am now a CPA who is very adamant about following ethics, both personally and professionally, and I always maintain my integrity.  That action could have had the potential to me getting licensed if it would have been on record.  Murder is more than a &quot;kid thing&quot;, and it takes a cold-hearted person to look into the eyes of another and watch the life drain out.  That isn't something that goes away with maturity, nor does the person go through a transformation when they hit their 18th birthday.  If we are talking about a 6 or 7 year old committing murder, then that is one thing, but by 15 or 16 years old they do know better, and I do feel they need to be held accountable for their actions.  The kids that did the school shooting in Arkansas are going to be released by their 21st birthdays, and one of the fathers is scared to death that this kid is going to get out and hurt someone because whatever it was that caused him to commit murder several years ago isn't going away as he matures.  Maturity comes when a person can really grasp the magnitude of their actions, but certain actions are serious to people of any age.<br>
<br>
Stacey <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mormongirl2>Mormongirl2</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 42<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/9/03 11:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=52.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   age of 8</span><hr size=1> I have to laugh here.  If getting baptized determines the rest of your life, there would not be so many athiests and agnostics here who were once baptized into religion.<br>
<br>
The reason we believe that a child can/should be baptized at age eight is because we believe that baptism is a saving ordinance.  Before the age of accountability, children are innocent and cannot sin, make mistakes yes, sin no.  After they have a grasp on right and wrong, they become accountible for their actions and can sin.  So in order to enter into a covenant with Christ.  ( I will do my part, try to be good and obedient to the gospel principles and He will forgive the sins of which I have repented) we are baptized.  Then we are confirmed members of the church and recieve the gift of the Holy Ghost, by the laying on of hands by an elder.<br>
<br>
But any person at any age can choose not to be a member of the church.  They either just stop participating or if they feel strongly enough about it they can have their name removed from the records of the church, which in effect nullifies their baptism.  <br>
<br>
HTH - Shirene <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=alek0>alek0</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/10/03 12:16 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=52.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   name removed from records</span><hr size=1> There are people who have found it quite difficult to remove their name from the records.<br>
