<br>
We believe that baptism is a saving ordinance.  Which in English means that in order to get to heaven you need to be baptized.  Since not everyone on this earth gets to hear the gospel of Jesus Christ and get babptized we provide this for them vicariously (Christ suffered for our sins vicariously, he did something for us we couldnt do on our own)  So we provide the opportunity to be baptized.   That does not mean that every person for whom we are baptized will accept that work.  It is still a choice, they can accept the baptism or they can reject it.<br>
<br>
Truth is absolute.  All roads don't lead to Rome.  Respecting someone's right to belief does not mean I have to aquiesse my own beliefs just to make em happy or comfortable.<br>
<br>
If we are right, which of course I believe we are.  It is a compassionate thing to give someone this necessary gift/opportunity, which we believe we are directed to do.  If we are wrong, I doubt God will judge someone for something we did for them.<br>
<br>
Thats my 2 cents on the matter.<br>
<br>
On having their names removed, it is a simple process.  You make the request in writing.  You are ex communicated.  Ex communication does involve a process called a church court.  Which really is just a meeting with the high council ( local leaders) to be sure that you understand what you are asking.  They want to make sure there isnt a resolvable concern.  ( my dad and dh's dad were both bishops and were involved in this process and it seemed pretty straigtforward to me)<br>
<br>
I think most people who leave just stop attending.<br>
<br>
-- Shirene<br>
